message: I see that it is possible http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1331385/how-can-i-see-incoming-commits-in-git
"git whatchanged origin.." will show you the commits between origin/master and master when you are on master.
What I want is to see incoming and outgoing changes for a specific remote (not origin)
you have to specify a branch
Thanks for the note about 'whatchanged' being deprecated.
which means 'what do i have locally that i haven't pushed yet
I want something like git whatchanged foo.. (obviously this is not working)
I have two remotes: origin and a second one let's call it foo
the 'whatchanged' command is deprecated - it does the same thing as log now
i like saying "git log master ^foo/master" which is the same thing just in what i think is a less confusing syntax
it means 'show me the commits that are reachable from your master branch that are not reachable from the remote 'foo/master' branch
and I keep getting fatal: ambiguous argument 'foo/master..': unknown revision or path not in the working tree.
IIRC this will only work if you're tracking the specific branch.
